          Marcus Aurelius Antoninus (121–180 CE) was Roman emperor from 161 to 180 CE and is often
          remembered as history’s clearest example of a philosopher king. While leading campaigns and
          governing a vast empire, he wrote private notes on character, mortality, and responsibility.
        </p>
